---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', text: 'Overview', level: 2 },
  { id: 'coverage-comparison', text: 'Coverage Comparison', level: 2 },
  { id: 'pricing', text: 'Pricing', level: 2 },
  { id: 'network-and-claims', text: 'Network and Claims', level: 2 },
  { id: 'who-should-choose', text: 'Who Should Choose Which', level: 2 },
  { id: 'verdict', text: 'Our Verdict', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'GeoBlue Review', href: '/providers/geoblue' },
  { title: 'Cigna Global Review', href: '/providers/cigna-global' },
  { title: 'Best for US Expats', href: '/best/us-expat-insurance' },
  { title: 'Aetna vs GeoBlue', href: '/compare/aetna-international-vs-geoblue' },
  { title: 'Mexico Insurance Guide', href: '/countries/mexico/insurance' },
];

const coverageColumns = [
  { key: 'feature', header: 'Feature' },
  { key: 'geoblue', header: 'GeoBlue' },
  { key: 'cigna', header: 'Cigna Global' },
];

const coverageRows = [
  { feature: 'US Network', geoblue: 'Blue Cross (largest)', cigna: '1.5M+ providers' },
  { feature: 'Inpatient Care', geoblue: true, cigna: true },
  { feature: 'Outpatient Care', geoblue: true, cigna: true },
  { feature: 'Mental Health', geoblue: true, cigna: true },
  { feature: 'Maternity', geoblue: 'Optional', cigna: 'Optional' },
  { feature: 'Dental', geoblue: 'Optional', cigna: 'Optional' },
  { feature: 'Medical Evacuation', geoblue: true, cigna: true },
  { feature: 'US Coverage Included', geoblue: 'Yes (core)', cigna: 'Add-on' },
  { feature: 'Annual Maximum', geoblue: '$1M-$5M', cigna: '$1M-Unlimited' },
];

const pricingColumns = [
  { key: 'profile', header: 'Profile' },
  { key: 'geoblue', header: 'GeoBlue' },
  { key: 'cigna', header: 'Cigna Global + US' },
];

const pricingRows = [
  { profile: 'Single, Age 30', geoblue: '$180-240/mo', cigna: '$200-260/mo' },
  { profile: 'Single, Age 45', geoblue: '$280-360/mo', cigna: '$320-400/mo' },
  { profile: 'Couple, Age 35', geoblue: '$360-480/mo', cigna: '$400-520/mo' },
  { profile: 'Family of 4', geoblue: '$550-750/mo', cigna: '$650-850/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="GeoBlue vs Cigna Global"
  description="Compare GeoBlue and Cigna Global for US expats. See which offers better US network access, coverage, and value."
  headline="GeoBlue vs Cigna Global: Which Is Better for US Expats?"
  subheadline="Both offer US coverage, but with different approaches. Here's how to choose between them."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/compare/geoblue-vs-cigna-hero-bg.png"
  heroImage="/images/pages/provider-card-generic.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Quotes from Both"
  ctaButtonHref="/best/us-expat-insurance"
>
    <h2 id="overview">Overview</h2>
  <p>
    GeoBlue and Cigna Global are both popular choices for international health insurance, but they serve different needs. Understanding their key differences will help you choose the right coverage for your situation abroad.
  </p>
  <p>
    GeoBlue is a Blue Cross Blue Shield company focused on international health coverage. Their main connection to the Blue Cross Blue Shield network and strong US ties. They're particularly popular among American expats who want continuity with US healthcare brands, with mid-range with good options for short and long-term coverage.
  </p>
  <p>
    Cigna Global is known for its extensive global network and strong customer service. They're known for their massive provider network with direct billing at over 1.5 million healthcare facilities worldwide. They tend to attract families and American expats who prioritize convenience, offering premium pricing but many feel the convenience justifies the cost.
  </p>
  <p>
    This comparison breaks down the key differences between these two providers so you can make an informed decision. We'll cover coverage options, pricing estimates, network access, claims processes, and help you determine which one makes more sense for your specific needs and budget.
  </p>

  <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">GeoBlue</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-600">
        <li>Blue Cross Blue Shield network access</li>
        <li>US coverage built into plans</li>
        <li>Designed for Americans abroad</li>
        <li>Strong telemedicine options</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Cigna Global</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-600">
        <li>Largest global provider network</li>
        <li>US coverage as optional add-on</li>
        <li>More plan customization options</li>
        <li>Stronger outside the US</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Both Providers"
    description="Get quotes from GeoBlue and Cigna Global for your situation."
    buttonText="Get Free Quotes"
    buttonHref="/best/us-expat-insurance"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="coverage-comparison">Coverage Comparison</h2>
  <p>
    The key difference is how they handle US coverage. GeoBlue includes it by default; Cigna charges extra for it.
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={coverageColumns} rows={coverageRows} />
  </div>

  <p>
    <strong>Key differences:</strong>
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>US network:</strong> GeoBlue uses Blue Cross Blue Shield—the largest US network. Cigna's US network is large but not as extensive</li>
    <li><strong>Plan structure:</strong> GeoBlue plans assume you'll use US care; Cigna treats it as an add-on</li>
    <li><strong>Maximum coverage:</strong> Cigna offers unlimited options; GeoBlue caps at $5M (still very high)</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="pricing">Pricing</h2>
  <p>
    When comparing prices, you need to factor in US coverage for Cigna. GeoBlue includes it; Cigna charges 40-60% more when you add it.
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={pricingColumns} rows={pricingRows} />
  </div>

  <p>
    <strong>Notes on pricing:</strong>
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>GeoBlue is often more cost-effective when US coverage is essential</li>
    <li>Cigna without US coverage is cheaper, but that defeats the purpose for most US expats</li>
    <li>Both offer high-deductible options to reduce premiums</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="Get Your Actual Price"
    description="Prices vary by age, location, and coverage choices."
    buttonText="Get a Quote"
    buttonHref="/best/us-expat-insurance"
  />

  <h2 id="network-and-claims">Network and Claims</h2>

  <h3>US Network Access</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>GeoBlue</strong> gives you access to the Blue Cross Blue Shield network—over 90% of US doctors and hospitals. This is a significant advantage if you frequently return to the US.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Cigna Global</strong> has a large US network but it's not as comprehensive as BCBS. You may have fewer in-network options in some areas.
  </p>

  <h3>International Coverage</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Cigna Global</strong> has the edge internationally with 1.5M+ providers worldwide and more direct-billing relationships outside the US.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>GeoBlue</strong> provides solid international coverage but their network is smaller outside the US. You may need to pay and file for reimbursement more often.
  </p>

  <h3>Claims Process</h3>
  <p>
    Both offer online claims submission. Cigna's portal is generally more polished. GeoBlue's process is straightforward but less feature-rich.
  </p>

  <h2 id="who-should-choose">Who Should Choose Which</h2>

  <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Choose GeoBlue If:</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-600">
        <li>You return to the US frequently</li>
        <li>BCBS network access is important</li>
        <li>You want US coverage included by default</li>
        <li>You have existing US doctors you want to keep</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Choose Cigna Global If:</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-600">
        <li>You spend most time outside the US</li>
        <li>You want the largest global network</li>
        <li>Direct billing abroad is a priority</li>
        <li>You want more plan customization</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="verdict">Our Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    For US expats who regularly return home, <strong>GeoBlue</strong> often makes more sense. The integrated BCBS network and included US coverage provide seamless care on both sides of the ocean.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Cigna Global</strong> is the better choice if you're truly global—spending significant time in multiple countries and only occasionally visiting the US. Their international network is unmatched.
  </p>
  <p>
    If you're unsure, consider where you'll actually receive most of your care. If the answer is "mostly in the US," lean toward GeoBlue. If it's "mostly abroad," Cigna Global with the US add-on may serve you better.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready to Decide?"
    description="Compare quotes from both providers based on your specific needs."
    buttonText="Compare Plans Now"
    buttonHref="/best/us-expat-insurance"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-8">
    <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">
      <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This comparison is for informational purposes only. Prices, coverage, and plan details change. We are not insurance brokers. Verify all information with the providers before purchasing.
    </p>
  </div>
</PageShell>
